  "prompt": "Are you actually supposed to break people's ribs when performing CPR?",
  "response": "Yes, it is actually quite common to break a person's ribs when performing CPR (cardiopulmonary resuscitation). The primary goal of CPR is to maintain circulation and oxygenation to the brain and vital organs by manually compressing the heart. Effective chest compressions require significant force to be exerted on the chest, which can sometimes result in fractured ribs or sternum.\n\nIt's important to remember that while rib fractures are a potential side effect, the priority in a life-threatening situation is to preserve life. Broken ribs can heal, but the consequences of not performing adequate CPR can be far more severe. Proper training in CPR techniques can help minimize this risk while maximizing the efficacy of the compressions.",
